be isolates the problem: the service root exists in the image, but native `ClassLoader.getResources(...)` returns a `resource:/...` URL, and Camel’s scanner doesn’t know how to walk that protocol as a jar or directory. That means the remaining test failure is caused by Camel’s scan implementation, not by missing file/constructor metadata anymore. I’m checking one last detail: what the `resource:/.../health-check/` stream actually contains, in case there’s a metadata-only way to feed the scanner a usable listing.\"}}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.apache.camel:camel-health:4.20.0/metadata-fix/codex.log:133:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_76\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"The native probe gave the decisive result: the remaining loader failure is not a missing resource entry anymore. Under native image, the health-check root is exposed as `resource:/META-INF/services/org/apache/camel/health-check/`; Camel’s `DefaultPackageScanResourceResolver` only knows how to walk real directories or jars, so it returns zero scan results even though the root and the specific descriptor file are both present. I’m checking whether Camel offers any built-in configuration hook for `resource:` scanning before I decide whether this turn should stop at the metadata-only fix plus a clear limitation.\"}}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.apache.camel:camel-health:4.20.0/metadata-fix/codex.log:135:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_77\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/usr/bin/bash -lc \\\"strings /tmp/metadata-forge-gradle/d983324bf342847c/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.apache.camel/camel-support/4.20.0/c02d452e928ac887813f84fdda95deb23827f02d/camel-support-4.20.0.jar | rg 'acceptableSchemes|package scan|resource:'\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":1,\"status\":\"failed\"}}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.apache.camel:camel-health:4.20.0/metadata-fix/codex.log:137:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_78\",\"type\"